who came from France to NY <i>c.</i> 1682 via the Netherlands and England and died in NJ <i>c.</i> 1700."]}]},{"name":"Jean","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Like   Jane   and   Joan  , a medieval variant of Old French <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Towards the end of the Middle Ages this form became largely confined to Scotland. In the 20th century it became more widely used in the English-speaking world and enjoyed a period of great popularity, but it is now out of fashion. Among numerous well-known and influential bearers are the British novelists  Jean Plaidy  (  Eleanor Hibbert ,  1910–93 ) and  Jean Rhys  (  Ella Gwendolen Rees Williams ,  1894–1979 ), British actress  Jean Simmons  (  1929–2010 ), and American-born actress  Jean Seberg  (  1938–79 ). It is also found as a variant spelling of the masculine name   Gene ."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]},{"name":"Jeane","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jean ."]}]},{"name":"II","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Loving’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Chevalier Jean II d'Ailly was born in 1190, in Ailly-le-Haut-Clocher, Somme, Hauts-de-France, France, his father, Chevalier Raould II d'Ailly, was 30 and his mother, Alix ou Aline de Boufflers, was 24. He married Hélène de Picquigny in 1217. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1234, at the age of 44."},"et":{"1190–1234":"1190–1234","1202–1265":"1202–1265","1202–Female":"1202–Surnud","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1220–1282":"1220–1282","1232–1299":"1232–1299","1160–1226":"1160–1226","1166–1231":"1166–1231","1190":"1190","1220":"1220","1231":"1231","1230":"1230","1282":"1282","1160":"1160","1217":"1217","1226":"1226","1202":"1202","1234":"1234","1299":"1299","1232":"1232","1166":"1166","1265":"1265"